Battery to Law Enforcement Officers, Fire Fighters or Commission Wardens

result.execSummary:
The defendant Chelsie M Eden was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Attempt Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

  Plea is F V  made. Sufficient factual basis to support the plea and the def is found guilty.
Nelson: Talked to the officer about this and he was open to resolving this w/o a felony conviction but she really went after him that evening. When it got to the point where she used profanities, it started escalating. She has a history here and  that's why we oppose expunction. 
Barton: Her actions that night were appalling and she will admit that but it's not who she is. Alc played a role in this. She acknowledges that she needs to address those issues and she's doing that. 
Def: I can't use alc as an excuse but it's the root of the problem. I don't remember a thing. It's not like me to act like that. When I read the report it didn't sound like me and I didn't even believe it was real. I would like expunction. 
Crt: You say that's not your character but this is the 2nd time you are resistant to officers under the influence of alc. Looking at your conduct, you're profane, assaultive to an officer; mouthy; immature and bratty. This is the 2nd time you've responded that way to an officer and looks like the officer was trying to help someone one might have needed assistance. I would be concerned about that if I were you. Barton makes a good suggestion but concerned of the monitoring and ensuring there's oversight for her if she were to fall short. I am reluctant to use probation but she had a similar incident 3 yrs ago and there needs to be oversight to ensure she succeeds and treatment needs are met
SENTENCE:
Sentence withheld - 12 mos probation on all 3 counts concurrent
Cond:  ct. 4 - 30 days CJ to be served on EM thru JS. AODA and follow thru w/ any treatment recommendations; the def is not to consume or possess any alc or controlled substances w/o Rx; no bars/taverns; random testing; NC w/ Lt. Klos except in the context of apology; any other assessment PO deems necessary; ltr of apology to Lt. Klos w/in 30 days and it must be approved by the PO. Pay DOC fees & CC. 3 days credit which will NOT be applied to the 30 days
Will defer 973.015 treatment until 4/1/16 and that will allow for the yr probation and one following it and if you are doing outstanding, taking positive steps in your life, I will consider it.
